---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/Eyebrow.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import FileTree from '../components/FileTree.astro';
import Step from '../components/Step.astro';

const TREE = `hello/
├── bock.project
├── .gitignore
├── src/
│   └── main.bock
└── tests/`;

const STARTER_BOCK = `fn main() {
  println("Hello, world!")
}`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Get started with Bock"
  description="Install Bock, write your first function, and build it for your stack."
>
  <Nav current="/get-started" />
  <main class="bock-doc">
    <header class="bock-doc__hero">
      <div class="bock-container">
        <Eyebrow>Documentation</Eyebrow>
        <h1 class="bock-doc__title">Get started with Bock</h1>
        <p class="bock-doc__lede">
          Install Bock, write your first function, and build it for your stack.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <Step n={1} title="Install">
      <p>Bock ships as a single binary for macOS, Linux, and Windows.</p>
      <p><strong>Cargo</strong> (any platform with Rust installed):</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`cargo install bock`} />
      <p><strong>Pre-built binaries:</strong> download from <a href="https://github.com/bock-lang/bock/releases">GitHub Releases</a> for macOS, Linux, and Windows.</p>
      <p>Verify the install:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock --version`} />
    </Step>

    <Step n={2} title="Your first project">
      <p>Scaffold a new project:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock new hello\ncd hello`} />
      <p>You'll get this layout:</p>
      <FileTree label="hello/">{TREE}</FileTree>
      <p>
        <code class="bock-inline-code">bock.project</code> is the project config (TOML, similar to <code class="bock-inline-code">Cargo.toml</code> or <code class="bock-inline-code">pyproject.toml</code>). It includes a commented-out <code class="bock-inline-code">[ai]</code> block. Bock uses rule-based code generation by default; AI is opt-in. <code class="bock-inline-code">src/main.bock</code> is the entry point. <code class="bock-inline-code">tests/</code> is where your tests go. The <code class="bock-inline-code">.gitignore</code> is pre-populated with sensible defaults including the <code class="bock-inline-code">.bock/</code> cache directory that gets created on first build.
      </p>
      <p>Open <code class="bock-inline-code">src/main.bock</code>. The starter prints <code class="bock-inline-code">"Hello, world!"</code>:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="src/main.bock" language="bock" code={STARTER_BOCK} />
      <p>Make it yours.</p>
    </Step>

    <Step n={3} title="Build for your target">
      <p>Bock supports JavaScript, TypeScript, Python, Rust, and Go in v1. The same source compiles to any of them.</p>
      <p>JavaScript:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock build --target js`} />
      <p>Go:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock build --target go`} />
      <p>The JavaScript output uses <code class="bock-inline-code">console.log</code> and ES modules. The Go output uses <code class="bock-inline-code">fmt.Println</code> and follows gofmt conventions. Idiomatic here means the generated code follows each language's conventions rather than mechanically translating Bock's syntax.</p>
    </Step>

    <Step n={4} title="Run it">
      <p>For development, run the source directly through the interpreter:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock run`} />
      <p>This skips codegen entirely, which makes the iteration loop fast.</p>
      <p>To run the compiled output, build first then invoke the target's runtime:</p>
      <CodeBlock filename="terminal" language="bash" code={`bock build --target js\nnode build/js/main.js`} />
      <p>The compiled JavaScript runs on Node without anything from Bock imported at runtime. The compiled output is your code. Bock isn't in the picture at runtime.</p>
    </Step>

    <Step n={5} title="Where to next">
      <p>The full language reference is at <a href="https://bocklang.org/docs">the documentation</a>.</p>
      <ul class="bock-doc__next">
        <li><strong>Language guide:</strong> types, effects, context annotations, the strictness system</li>
        <li><strong>Stdlib reference:</strong> core modules and what they emit per target</li>
        <li><strong>Examples:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/bock-lang/bock/tree/main/examples">examples on GitHub</a></li>
        <li><strong>Discussions:</strong> <a href="https://github.com/bock-lang/bock/discussions">GitHub Discussions</a></li>
        <li><strong>Subreddit:</strong> <a href="https://reddit.com/r/bocklang">the Bock subreddit</a></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="bock-doc__caption">Bock is open source under the MIT License.</p>
    </Step>

    <section class="bock-cta">
      <div class="bock-container bock-cta__inner">
        <p class="bock-cta__body">Back to the homepage when you're ready.</p>
        <Button variant="ghost" href="/">Home</Button>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('[data-bock-copy]').forEach((btn) => {
    btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const code = btn.dataset.code ?? '';
      navigator.clipboard?.writeText(code);
      const original = btn.textContent;
      btn.textContent = 'Copied';
      window.setTimeout(() => { btn.textContent = original; }, 1400);
    });
  });
</script>
